name: Garry Shead First Vintage
description:
First Vintage was the first of three etchings Garry commenced on Skopelos in June, 2010. The print has undergone three states, which means that the artist has published small numbers of different versions of the etching, while he has tried to resolve it to his satisfaction.

This image is a black and white version of STATE 3. It is already available from us, while a colour version is available from Falls Gallery (see their website: www.fallsgallery.com.au)

STATE 4 is about to be editioned in colour. The face of the woman has changed; otherwise the image will be much as you see here.

PRINT DETAILS (as illustrated):
TITLE: First Vintage
MEDIUM: B/W Etching
DIMENSIONS: 24.5 x 33cms

PUBLICATION OF STATE 4 IN COLOUR EXPECTED IN MAY 2011.
ORDERS TAKEN.

name: Garry Shead Dionysis at Pokolbin
description:
Garry commenced the etching on the Greek island of Skopelos in 2010 whilst with a group of Australian artists who were invited to work with Basil and Mats for a fortnight. Garry has been painting on the theme of winemaking for some time and was pleased to discover that a small vineyard was situated next door to the Skopelos studio! Mythological Greek creatures soon inhabited the etchings.

PRINT DETAILS:
Title: Dionysis at Pokolbin
Medium: Colour etching
Dimensions: 24.5 x 33cms

name: DESERT MOB 20TH ANNIVERSARY PRINT BOX SET
description:
BASIL HALL EDITIONS presents the DESERT MOB 20TH ANNIVERSARY PRINT FOLIO - 38 Art Centres; 40 original woodcuts

As part of the celebration of the twentieth anniversary of desert mob, basil hall editions is proud to present the first complete collection of prints from each of the art centres currently affiliated with desart, the Association of Central Australian art and craft centres.

The Art Centres were each sent a wood block, tools and instructions in early 2010 and invited to select an artist to cut, burn, drill or incise the block in some way. Basil Hall editions staff would then make a small edition of 20 from each block. 

Ten of these prints would be given to the artist to sell through his or her art centre and ten would be for sale in complete sets, to be boxed in specially made folios decorated with individually commissioned tjanpi coil designs. The 40 blocks would also be mounted and used to produce 15 large panel pieces. 

In September 2010 the blocks themselves, the panel, the folios and the 40 individual prints were exhibited at the Araluen arts centre as part of desert mob 2010.

name: COLLECTORS’ FOLIO - Series IV
description:
The 2009 team at Basil Hall Editions (BHE) and six talented indigenous artists from northern and central Australia are proud to present Series IV of BHE’s Collectors’ Folios.

Over the last four years we have now presented you with four series of superb etchings, silkscreens and relief prints; twenty four perfect excuses to start an art collection, gather inexpensive works by major Australian artists or give a unique gift.

These prints have been made in collaboration with Indigenous people from remote communities in the Northern Territory, Queensland, Western and South Australia. Basil Hall and his printers have travelled many thousands of kilometres to work on the plates, screens or blocks with the artists, before returning to the Darwin studio of BHE to proof and edition the prints by hand.

Once the prints have dried, they are carefully numbered out of 100 and have the studio stamp applied to the bottom corner. They are sent to the artists for their approval and signature and return to the studio for packing in their specially designed folios.

This co-publication between the Art Centres, artists and BHE means that the artists are paid up front for their work, while the prints are wholesaled by the Art Centres themselves and BHE.

name: Judy Napangardi Watson - Kurrkara Jukurrpa (Desert Oak Dreaming from Mina Mina)
description:
Kurrkara is the shade tree where the women in this painting sat down to rest at Mina Mina, an important ceremonial place belonging to Japanangka/Japangardi men and Napanangka/Napangardi women. Mina Mina and the associated land is far to the west of Yuendumu in the sandhill country. Napanangka and Napangardi women are shown here collecting Jintiparnta (Edible fungus) at Kantakarlangu, an area that is also called Mina Mina. Ancestral women travelled from here to the north through Janyinki and other places then to the east to Alcoota country. There are a number of Mulju (water soakages) and a clay pan at Mina Mina and it is here that the women danced and performed various ceremonies. As a result Karla-ngu (digging sticks) rose up out of the ground and it is these implements that the women carried with them on their long journey east.

name: Marika Patrick - Purnululu
description:
Marika Patrick has depicted the beehive domes of her family’s traditional country - the World Heritage-listed Bungle Bungles (Purnululu National Park). This is Patrick’s grandmother’s country where her great-great-grandmother used to live. Patrick says it was good hunting country and that she still visits sometimes. There are many sites within Purnululu with special significance to Patrick and to Gija people.

name: Custodians: Country and Culture
description:
This is a boxed folio of ten limited edition prints by ten outstanding Indigenous Australian artists. Custodians celebrates the strength and diversity of leading Aboriginal contemporary artists in a representative survey of art from the Top End, Kimberley and Central Australia. Custodians is defined by a carefully focused curatorial process in which artists were selected and invited to participate on the strength of their artistic output and cultural standing. 

01 Bardayal Nadjamerrek
Ankung Kunred 2008
etching and screenprint, 50 x 39cm
Collaborators/plate-makers: Basil Hall and Monique Auricchio
Printers: Basil Hall, Jacqueline Gribbin and Clinton Barker

02 Dorothy Napangardi
Salt on Mina Mina 2008
etching, 50 x 39cm
Collaborator/plate-maker: Basil Hall
Printers: Basil Hall and Merran Sierakowski

03 Gulumbu Yunupingu
Garak 2008

Printers: Jacqueline Gribbin and Monique Auricchio

04 Judy Napangardi Watson
Mia Mina Jukurrpa 2008
screenprint, 39 x 50cm
Collaborators/plate-makers: Warlukurlangu staff and Basil Hall
Printer: Clinton Barker

05 Gawirrin Gumana
Baraltja 2008
etching, 50 x 39cm
Collaborators/plate-makers: Buku–Larrnggay Mulka staff and Basil Hall
Printers: Basil Hall and Merran Sierakowski

06 Janangoo Butcher Cherel
Girndi 2008
etching and screenprint, 50 x 39cm
Collaborator/plate-maker: Basil Hall

07 Jean Baptiste Apuatimi
Jirtaka (sawfish) 2008
screenprint, 50 x 39cm

08 Kathleen Petyarre
Arnkerrth 2008
etching and screenprint, 39 x 50cm
